'''John Altschuler''' (born July 10, 1963) is an American television and film producer and writer.

==Life and career==
Altschuler grew up in a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bloom|first=Nate|authorlink= |title=Jewish entertainers well-represented at Emmy Awards |publisher=Saint Louis Jewish Light|date=September 14, 2017 |url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/features/article_2cfe1400-989e-11e7-90f4-5ff77ddf0656.html|accessdate=}}</ref> in [[Carbondale, Illinois]]. He then moved with his family to [[Cary, North Carolina]], later attended the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], and co-created the first student-produced comedy show on UNC Student Television.<ref name="HuffPost">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/john-altschuler-and-dave-krinsky|title=John Altschuler and Dave Krinsky: Comedy writers|work=[[Huffington Post]] (US edition)|publisher= Huffingtonost.com|access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref>

He began his career as a writer for the humour magazine ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]'', together with [[Dave Krinsky]], whom he met and began collaborating creatively with while at UNC-Chapel Hill,<ref name="HuffPost"/> which became a collaboration that continued in the years to come. After selling their screenplays to [[Warner Brothers]], Universal and [[Studio Canal Plus]], they moved to [[Hollywood]] and began working as assistant producers for the [[HBO]] series ''[[The High Life (1996 TV series)|The High Life]]''.<ref name="HuffPost"/>  In 1997, Altschuler and Krinsky became writers on 20th Century Fox’s ''[[King of the Hill]]''. They worked there for 13 years and ran the show for the final seven seasons.<ref name="HuffPost"/>

In 2008, they formed Ternion Productions, a film and television production company with [[Mike Judge]].<ref name="HuffPost"/>  In 2009, Altschuler, Judge, and Krinsky co-created the show ''[[The Goode Family]].''<ref name="HuffPost"/>  In 2011, they executive produced and wrote several episodes of [[MTV]]’s return of ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]''.

Altschuler and Krinsky also co-wrote various features, including ''[[Role Models]]'', ''[[Blades of Glory]]'' and ''[[Extract (film)|Extract]]''. He also produced the Napoleonic War comedy ''The Adventures of [[Brigadier Gerard]]'' from his script based on the short stories of Sir [[Arthur Conan Doyle]].

In 2013, Altschuler, Judge, and Krinsky co-created the HBO series ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]''. In addition, they are working on an animated [[Woody Woodpecker]] feature. They are also writing and producing ''Brigadier Gerard'', a feature with [[Steve Carell]] attached to play Brigadier Gerard and [[Ricky Gervais]] attached to play Napoleon.

In 2015, Altschuler, Krinsky and [[Jeff Stilson]] co-created the sitcom series ''[[Lopez]]'', starring [[George Lopez]]. [[TV Land]] gave a 12-episode straight-to-series order in August 2015. The series premiered on March 30, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |author=TV Land press release |date=February 8, 2016 |title="Lopez" Premieres March 30th on TV Land |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2016/02/08/lopez-premieres-march-30th-on-tv-land-607224/20160208tvland01/ |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=9 February 2016}}</ref> On June 3, 2016, TV Land renewed ''Lopez'' for a second season.<ref>{{cite web |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=June 4, 2016 |url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/george-lopez-comedy-renewed-second-season-tv-land-1201766920/ |title=George Lopez Comedy Renewed For Second Season By TV Land |work=Deadline}}</ref>

Altschuler has received several Emmy nominations and has won an [[Environmental Media Award]], and also a [[SXSW|SXSW Film Award]], which was shared along with Krinsky and [[Carson D. Mell]] for their writing work for ''Silicon Valley''.

